<p>The Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms are now the most widely accepted answer to t=
he question: How can one correctly construct a set? Of course, these axioms=
 are more restrictive than Cantor=E2=80=99s Comprehension Principle; howeve=
r, no one, in over 100 years, has been able to derive a contradiction from =
these axioms. Moreover, all of the classic results (excluding the paradoxes=
) that were derived using Cantor=E2=80=99s na=C3=AFve set theory can be der=
ived from the Zermelo-Fraenkel axioms.</p>
<p>It is a remarkable fact that essentially all mathematical objects can be=
 defined as sets within Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory. For example, functions=
, relations, the natural numbers, and the real numbers can be defined withi=
n Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory. Hence, effectively all theorems of mathemati=
cs can be considered as statements about sets and proven from the Zermelo-F=
raenkel axioms.</p>
